As an Irishman, I have a fair idea of semi sensible ‘Irish’ themed bars.  Now the place did look the part, and the beer selection was nice and sensible as it should be.  Wait staff although fairly attentive in part, just appeared to lack any real care or passion for their work.  The food was the ultimate down fall, I ordered what was know as a disassembled Shepard’s pie. Essentially the ingredients were all independent, that does certainly remove the joy of the flavours infusing in the oven. And there just wasn’t enough potato, in fact not enough of anything, the dish was small. My nine year old daughter would eat more than that.  Ultimately and what made it worse, the food was served stone cold. Not just the so called Shepard’s pie, my partners Mac cheese was stone cold too. Upon complaining to the wait staff about the temperature of the food, they simply put it in the microwave (the part eaten elements of the dish were still present after warm up). That’s just unacceptable.  Chicago is home to some great Irish bars, this one is certainly for the folks unfamiliar with how good our food can be.

Local feel in a downtown hotel bar.  Kitty O'Shea's feels like a neighborhood Irish bar, although it's located in the lovely Hilton on Michigan Avenue.  I went for St. Patrick's Day after work and it was very lively, with tasty Irish appetizers, like corned beef sandwiches, and friendly service. They even had a live Irish band.

Had some friends over and we decided to take a stroll through Grant Park. After? Well drinks and a light dinner was in order and one of them was staying at the Hilton and mentioned wanting to try O'Sheas. So we strolled across the street to try it out.  For being in a Hilton I figured hey, they have to be good. Also it's an Irish bar and I LOVE Irish bars for the food (drink selections as well as they usually have great cider choices.) Also the Hilton is known for great service.  On the appetizer list we tried the wings as well as the fried pickles and cheese curds. The wings were a bit bland though the fried pickles and curds were fantastic. A 50/50 sign on how the meal would be but with how much we enjoyed the pickles and curds we figured we were gonna luck out.  Around the table were orders of fish and chips and the burger which were all pretty bland sadly. I don't know what else to say. They weren't bad they just seemed to be lacking from what everyone was expecting.  All I can say is at least they had bottles of Magners. One of my ciders of choice. It would have been better if it was on tap but hey, at least that part was enjoyable. Of course, that was until it was time for a second round. Also it was a little pricey compared to half the other places we could have gone in the area that had Magners.  Overall, not a great experience.

This pub is better than would assume for a hotel joint. The menu as expected features typical bar fare but it is far above average. The Fish & Chips for example are made from very fresh fish and the chips are very decent, too.  A problem is the gloomy interior that features a strange smell. It's also very chilly and long sleeves are recommended.  The by far best thing about the place however is the random and very mixed crowd which often consists of conference goers. People quickly mix up at the bar inside and I found myself suddenly surrounded by an architect, two nurses, a staunch Republican from Michigan and members of a tech start-up. In the end it does very well what a pub should do.
